      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2008_Solutions_2008s_page_005_24",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "For n > k + 1, group the k-limited involutions into classes based on their actions on k + 2,...,n. Note that for C a class and o € C, the set of elements of A = {1,..,k + 1} which map into A under o depends only on C, not on o. Call this set S(C); then the size of C is exactly the number of involutions of S(C). Consequently, C is even unless S(C) has at most one element. However, the element 1 cannot map out of A because we are looking at k-limited involutions. Hence if S(C) has one element and o € C, we must have o (1) = 1. Since o is k-limited and o (2) cannot belong to A, we must have o (2) = k + 2. By induction, for i = 3, ...,k + 1, we must have o i) = k+i.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563909892474611,
          0.6351686508466557,
          0.9210526380050044,
          0.8212209302150003
        ],
        "order": 20
      }
